05077nam a22007815i 9780674065086DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20122012mau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)840442194  a97806740650867 a10.4159/harvard.97806740650862doi  a(DE-B1597)178178  a(OCoLC)835640673  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 7aLAW0150002bisacsh1 aWaldron, Jeremy, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Harm in Hate Speech /cJeremy Waldron. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (264 p.) :b1 line illustration  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Oliver Wendell Holmes Lectures, 2009. ;v200900tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgments -- tContents -- t1. Approaching Hate Speech -- t2. Anthony Lewis’s Freedom for the Thought That We Hate -- t3. Why Call Hate Speech Group Libel? -- t4. The Appearance of Hate -- t5. Protecting Dignity or Protection from Offense? -- t6. C. Edwin Baker and the Autonomy Argument -- t7. Ronald Dworkin and the Legitimacy Argument -- t8. Toleration and Calumny -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEvery liberal democracy has laws or codes against hate speech—except the United States. For constitutionalists, regulation of hate speech violates the First Amendment and damages a free society. Against this absolutist view, Jeremy Waldron argues powerfully that hate speech should be regulated as part of our commitment to human dignity and to inclusion and respect for members of vulnerable minorities.Causing offense—by depicting a religious leader as a terrorist in a newspaper cartoon, for example—is not the same as launching a libelous attack on a group’s dignity, according to Waldron, and it lies outside the reach of law. But defamation of a minority group, through hate speech, undermines a public good that can and should be protected: the basic assurance of inclusion in society for all members. A social environment polluted by anti-gay leaflets, Nazi banners, and burning crosses sends an implicit message to the targets of such hatred: your security is uncertain and you can expect to face humiliation and discrimination when you leave your home.Free-speech advocates boast of despising what racists say but defending to the death their right to say it. Waldron finds this emphasis on intellectual resilience misguided and points instead to the threat hate speech poses to the lives, dignity, and reputations of minority members. Finding support for his view among philosophers of the Enlightenment, Waldron asks us to move beyond knee-jerk American exceptionalism in our debates over the serious consequences of hateful speech.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aLAW / Communications.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK GESAMTPAKET / COMPLETE PACKAGE 2012z9783110288995oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK PACKAGE LAW  2012z978311029381408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK PAKET RECHTSWISSENSCHAFTEN 2012z9783110288919oZDB-23-DGC08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013 (Canada)z978311075606708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044220540uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/harvard.978067406508640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674065086423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780674065086.jpg  a978-3-11-029381-4  E-BOOK PACKAGE LAW  2012b2012  a978-3-11-044220-5  Harvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-075606-7  HUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013 (Canada)b2013  aEBA_BACKALL  